.TH FORK 2 "2025" "Nightingale" "Nightingale System Calls"
.SH NAME
fork \- create a new process
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #include <unistd.h>
.PP
.BI "pid_t fork(void);"
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B fork()
creates a new process by duplicating the calling process.
The new process is called the child process.
The calling process is referred to as the parent process.
.PP
The child process is an exact copy of the parent process except for the following:
.IP \(bu 3
The child has its own unique process ID (PID).
.IP \(bu
The child's parent process ID is the same as the parent's process ID.
.IP \(bu
The child does not inherit the parent's memory locks.
.IP \(bu
Process resource utilizations are reset to zero in the child.
.IP \(bu
The child's set of pending signals is initially empty.
.PP
The child process has its own copy of the parent's file descriptor table.
File descriptors refer to the same open file descriptions as the parent.
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, the PID of the child process is returned in the parent,
and 0 is returned in the child.
On failure, \-1 is returned in the parent, no child process is created,
and
.I errno
is set to indicate the error.
.SH ERRORS
.TP
.B ENOMEM
Insufficient kernel memory to allocate necessary structures.
